'''Bhatt Balh''' was a [[Sikh]] [[Brahmin]] bard in the court of [[Guru Arjan]], whose five hymns are present in ''[[Guru Granth Sahib]]'', the holy book of Sikhs.<ref>{{cite book |page=cxx |title=The Ādi-Granth, Or: The Holy Scriptures of the Sikhs |first=Ernst |last=Trumpp |publisher=W.H. Allen |date=1877}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |page=36 |title=The Encyclopedia of Sikhism| first=H. S. |last=Singha |publisher=Hemkunt Press |date=2000 |isbn=9788170103011}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |page=8 |title=unknown |journal=The Sikh Review |volume=55 |issue=1–6 |publisher=Sikh Cultural Centre |date=2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thesikhencyclopedia.com/scriptures/sri-guru-granth-sahib-and-guru-gobind-singhs-bani/bhatt-bani |work=The Sikh Encyclopedia |publisher=Gateway to Sikhism |title=BHATT BANI |accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref> The title [[Bhatt]] is given to learned Brahmins.

