{{About||a [[Counties of Iran|county of Iran]] of [[Khuzestan Province]]|Khorramshahr County|the capital city of this county of Iran|Khorramshahr|the [[Chili pepper]] [[dip (food)|dip]] originally from [[Aleppo]]|muhammara}}
{{Islamism sidebar}}
'''Muhammerah''' or '''Muhammira''' ("The Crimson, The Red") were [[Mazdak]]i groups such as the followers of [[al-Muqanna]], the [[Khurramites]] and the Kūl’īyyah. The members of these groups were active in region of modern [[Khorramshahr]] in [[Khorramshahr County]], [[Khuzestan Province]], [[Iran]].{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=July 2017}}

== Members ==
The Khurramites were those who followed the charismatic individuals [[Babak Khorramdin]] and [[Mazyar]].

=== Turkic Kaysanites ===
{{Shia Islam|Branches}}
[[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] [[Muslim sects]] included followers of ''[[Abu Muslim Khorasani|Bû’ Müslim’îyye]], Muhammerah, and [[Ishaq al-Turk|Ishâk at-Türk’îyye]] [[madh'hab]]s,'' all of them were the extension of “Rizâm’îyyah”, “Riyâh’îyyah” and “Râvend’îyyah” [[madh'hab]]s. All these [[madh'hab]]s had a shared doctrines of a belief in the [[incarnation]] belief of their [[Imamate|Imams]]. Like “[[Mukhtar al-Thaqafi|Mukhtâr’îyyah]]”, “[[Abu Hashim|Hâshim’îyyah]]” and “[[Khashabiyya Shia]]”, they were all from the [[Ghulat]] [[Shia]] [[madh'hab]] of [[Kaysanites Shia|Keysân’îyyah]] defending the godness of [[Muhammad ibn al-Hanafiyyah]], another son of [[Ali]] from his wife [[Khawlah bint Ja'far]].<ref>Mustafa Öz, ''[[Madh'hab]]s Tarihi ve Terimleri Sözlüğü,'' Ensar Yayıncılık, İstanbul, 2011. ''([[Kaysanites Shia|Keysân’îyye]] (Muhtâr’îyye/Keysân’îyyet-ûl-Hullas, Hâşim’îyye (Harb’îyye, Muâv’îyye/Cennâh’îyye (Hâris’îyye), Beyân’îyye), Râvend’îyye (Rizâm’îyye ([[Abu Muslim Khorasani|Bû’ Müslim’îyye]] ([[Sunpadh|Sinbâd’îyye]], Berkûk’îyye, Havâl’îyye), Muhammira ([[Al-Muqanna|Mukannaʿîyye]], [[Babak Khorramdin|Hürremdîn’îyye]] ([[Babak Khorramdin|Bâbek’îyye]], [[Maziar|Mazyâr’îyye]], [[Qizilbash]]s), Kûl’îyye), [[Ishaq al-Turk|Ishâk at-Türk’îyye]]), Riyâh’îyye), [[Khashabiyya Shia|Kebr’îyye]]) [[madh'hab]]s).''</ref>

According to [[:tr:Abdülbaki Gölpınarlı|Abdülbaki Gölpınarlı]], The [[Qizilbash]] were the spiritual descendants of the Khurramites.<ref>Roger M. Savory (Source: [[:tr:Abdülbaki Gölpınarlı|Abdülbaki Gölpınarlı]]), Encyclopaedia of Islam, "Kizil-Bash", Online Edition 2005.</ref>
